issue.title: Limit resources that can be accessed trough the proxy
issue.body:
When using this proxy to expose kubernetes api to external (read: non-trusted) users a very helpful option would be to limit what API groups are exposed trough proxy. This way one can be sure that the external user is only allowed to interact with certain APIs (eg. allow interacting only Deploymens or a cusom resource but do not allow user to list Nodes for example).

Would a PR for his make sense?

issue.title: Networking broken when using dind-rootless
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
Running wget or ping on [github.com](https://github.com) returns _bad address_ error.

**To Reproduce**
When using this image with dind-rootless, domains like [github.com](https://github.com) or [bitpoke.io](https://bitpoke.io) are not resolved properly, whereas [google.com](https://google.com) does resolve.

**Expected behavior**
All valid domains should resolve properly.

**Console Output**
```
#4 0.522 + wget -O /usr/bin/jq https://github.com/stedolan/jq/releases/download/jq-1.6/jq-linux64
#4 0.523 wget: bad address 'github.com'
```

**Additional context**
Might be related to https://gitlab.alpinelinux.org/alpine/aports/-/issues/11879 and https://github.com/alpinelinux/docker-alpine/issues/155 and might be caused by this commit: 3f935302f43896bef7240b9bd80a8c6f4c5cac4b

comment.body:
You can reproduce it by running docker-in-docker in rootless mode (`dind-rootless` tag from https://hub.docker.com/_/docker).

We are using dind-rootless in our CI pipelines and up until 3f935302f43896bef7240b9bd80a8c6f4c5cac4b we did not had any networking issues.
